  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT283-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ poruḷvayiṉ pirintavaḻi āṟṟāḷ eṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikku “avar piriya
          āṟṟēṉ āyiṉēṉ allēṉ avar pōyiṉa kāṉattut taṉmai niṉaintu vēṟuppaṭṭēṉ” eṉṟu kiḻatti
          colliyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER [with the words] “As he separates I have
          not been one who has not the strength; I have changed at the thought of the kind of forest
          he has gone into.”, to the confidante who was anxious she would not have the strength when
          HE separated because of wealth. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT283">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> uḷḷatu citaippō ruḷareṉap paṭāa</l>
          <l> rillōr vāḻkkai yiraviṉu miḷiveṉac</l>
          <l> colliya vaṉmai teḷiyak kāṭṭic</l>
          <l> ceṉṟaṉar vāḻi tōḻi yeṉṟuṅ</l>
          <l> kūṟṟat taṉṉa kolaivēṉ maṟava</l>
          <l> rāṟṟirun talki vaḻaṅkunarc cekutta</l>
          <l> paṭumuṭai paruntupārt tirukku</l>
          <l> neṭumū tiṭaiya nīri lāṟē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>He went, oh friend,</l>
          <l>after he had clearly shown [his] strength, which said <note place="foot"> Being a <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam, colliya </term> presumably must have <term xml:lang="ta"> vaṇmai </term> as subject: it is strength speaking out of him.</note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">“more disgraceful than begging is the living of those in the house</l>
          <l rend="indent2"> by those who are not entitled, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> illōr </term> must refer to men who stay in the house = at home instead of going out to make wealth, and <term xml:lang="ta"> paṭāar </term> an apposition to <term xml:lang="ta"> illōṟ </term>. </note> since they are wasters</l>
          <l rend="indent9">of what is there.”<note place="foot">  Literally this is a second sentence of direct speech embedded into the first. Presumably this is the attitude towards the matter of work generally expressed by people and shared by HIM. </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent">– along the waterless paths, long [and] old ways, <note place="foot"> What is expressed by <term xml:lang="ta"> iṭaiya </term>? Since it is marked as a n.pl., it must be construed as an pronominal noun referring to <term xml:lang="ta"> āṟu </term>. Perhaps it is the head noun of <term xml:lang="ta"> irukkum </term> of line 7, and the attribute <term xml:lang="ta"> neṭu </term>, "long", suggests that the meaning of <term xml:lang="ta"> iṭai </term> is rather "way" here, but what is the difference between <term xml:lang="ta"> āṟu </term> and <term xml:lang="ta"> iṭai </term>? </note></l>
          <l rend="indent2">where kites are perched [and] look out for flesh, coming up</l>
          <l rend="indent3">as the bold ones <note place="foot"> Cām./Trad. understand the <term xml:lang="ta"> maṟavar</term> to be dangerous inhabitants of <term xml:lang="ta"> pālai</term>. It should, however, be considered whether this is not rather an epithet for the <term xml:lang="ta"> kaḷvar</term>, who otherwise have the same function and are described in the same way (watching out for travellers, having bows etc.; cf. also KT 297.1). </note> with spears always murderous</l>
          <l rend="indent6">like the god of death</l>
          <l rend="indent2">lay in wait on the way <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> iruntu alki</term>: the absolutive presumably makes clear that the subject is not <term xml:lang="ta"> vaḻaṅkunar </term> but <term xml:lang="ta"> maṟavar</term>.</note> [and] kill <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> cekutta </term>: this <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam </term> is definitely odd. If the way of construction as shown above is correct, one would rather want an infinitive.</note> wanderers.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
